Australia strongly opposes Japan's plans to expand whaling in Antarctic waters, fearing damage to their perception of Japan.
Despite this, they won't board Japanese ships to avoid piracy accusations.
Environment Minister Ian Campbell warns of Japan's reputation risk if they persist.
Japan, known for whale meat, resumed whaling under a loophole for "research."
Australia aims to prevent commercial and scientific whaling internationally.
Prime Minister Howard urges Japan to reconsider its Antarctic whale harvest expansion.
Legal challenges against Japanese whaling in Australian waters have been dismissed, prompting animal rights groups to consider boycotts.
Japan's push to increase its whale hunt faces global criticism.
